{"summary":"Both amendments identify real robustness issues in the journal-repair path. The first is an observability gap that can silently turn serde failures into duplicate journal entries, and the second is a real forward-compatibility tradeoff from strict parsing that is not currently documented near the relevant types.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-8-866eda73","decision":"accept","rationale":"`json_fill_none` in `src/adapters/fs.rs` collapses `to_value`/`from_value` failures into `None`, and its callers already use `None` to mean an ordinary merge rejection. In `repairable_start_event` and `repairable_completion_event`, that makes a serde failure indistinguishable from a legitimate conflict and falls through to appending a duplicate event. The current structs are simple, so the immediate risk is low, but the helper is explicitly designed to absorb future optional fields; at minimum, emitting a warning on serde failure is technically justified."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-772de23c","decision":"accept","rationale":"`#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]` on the milestone journal detail structs means an older binary cannot parse a newer entry once an extra field has been written. In this codebase that parse failure does not corrupt data, but it does disable the in-place repair merge and can cause duplicate start/completion events to accumulate after rollback. The existing comments explain the anti-drift intent, but they do not document this rollback/forward-compatibility tradeoff, so accepting the amendment at least as a documentation improvement is warranted; switching to lenient runtime parsing is a separate design choice."}]}